      ✩                        How to Get Started |_|                              ✩
      ✩  /....................................................................../  ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  Download the release for your architecture directly from GitHub:          ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩          ╔══════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗          ✩
      ✩          ║ https://github.com/apology-is-policy/hyades/releases ║          ✩
      ✩          ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝          ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  The release ships with install scripts for MacOS, Linux, and Windows:     ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩                      ┌──────────────────────────────┐                      ✩
      ✩                      │ # Unixes:                    │                      ✩
      ✩                      │ editor-configs/install.sh    │                      ✩
      ✩                      │ # Windows:                   │                      ✩
      ✩                      │ .\editor-configs\install.ps1 │                      ✩
      ✩                      └──────────────────────────────┘                      ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  This will:                                                                ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩    ● Install the two core executables and add them to your PATH.           ✩
      ✩    ● If there’s a Helix installation, it will register itself with Helix   ✩
      ✩    ● The same with Neovim                                                  ✩
      ✩    ● It will typeset something to the console to test the installation.    ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  You are  invited to build from  source, which is very easy – after  all,  ✩
      ✩  𝐻𝑦𝑎δες has no binary dependencies whatsover.                              ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩                      ___                 _                                 ✩
      ✩                     | _ \ _  _ _ _  _ _ (_)_ _  __ _                       ✩
      ✩                     |   /| || | ' \| ' \| | ' \/ _` |                      ✩
      ✩                     |_|_\ \_,_|_||_|_||_|_|_||_\__, |                      ✩
      ✩                       I’m okay to go, okay to go! |_/                      ✩
      ✩  /....................................................................../  ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  Let’s use 𝐻𝑒𝑙𝑖𝑥 for our “Hello World”, since it works out of the box and  ✩
      ✩  VSCode requires an extension and some tinkering with the settings. 𝐻𝑒𝑙𝑖𝑥  ✩
      ✩  is a modal editor that you can download here:                             ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩                        ┌──────────────────────────┐                        ✩
      ✩                        │ https://helix-editor.com │                        ✩
      ✩                        └──────────────────────────┘                        ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  Re-run the install script – now that you actualy have 𝐻𝑒𝑙𝑖𝑥, 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες will  ✩
      ✩  install itself into it. Now create a new Cassilda file:                   ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐  ✩
      ✩  │ > hx hello.cld                                                       │  ✩
      ✩  └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘  ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  Once in 𝐻𝑒𝑙𝑖𝑥, switch to some normal theme that  supports syntax highli-  ✩
      ✩  ghting: [:theme dark_plus], and we’re ready for our program:              ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩    1:  │  hello                                                            ✩
      ✩    2:  │                                                                   ✩
      ✩    3:  │  The \textbf{Riemann curvature tensor} is a central               ✩
      ✩    4:  │  mathematical tool in the theory of general relativity.           ✩
      ✩    5:  │                                                                   ✩
      ✩    6:  │  \subtitle[\textit{Riemann Curvature Tensor}]{$$                  ✩
      ✩    7:  │      R^\rho{}_{\sigma\mu\nu} =                                    ✩
      ✩    8:  │      \partial_\mu\Gamma^\rho_{\nu\sigma} -                        ✩
      ✩    9:  │      \partial_\nu\Gamma^\rho_{\mu\sigma} +                        ✩
      ✩    10: │      \Gamma^\rho_{\mu\lambda}\Gamma^\lambda_{\nu\sigma} -         ✩
      ✩    11: │      \Gamma^\rho_{\nu\lambda}\Gamma^\lambda_{\mu\sigma}           ✩
      ✩    12: │  $$}                                                              ✩
      ✩    13: │                                                                   ✩
      ✩    14: │  end                                                              ✩
      ✩    15: │  cassilda: hello                                                  ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩        ↓↓↓            ↓↓↓           ↓↓↓           ↓↓↓           ↓↓↓        ✩
      ✩  ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐  ✩
      ✩  │ The 𝐑𝐢𝐞𝐦𝐚𝐧𝐧  𝐜𝐮𝐫𝐯𝐚𝐭𝐮𝐫𝐞 𝐭𝐞𝐧𝐬𝐨𝐫 is a central  mathematical tool in the │  ✩
      ✩  │ theory of general relativity.                                        │  ✩
      ✩  │                                                                      │  ✩
      ✩  │                ρ         ρ       ρ     ρ  λ     ρ  λ                 │  ✩
      ✩  │               𝑅     = ∂ Γ   − ∂ Γ   + Γ  Γ   − Γ  Γ                  │  ✩
      ✩  │                 σμν    μ νσ    ν μσ    μλ νσ    νλ μσ                │  ✩
      ✩  │                                                                      │  ✩
      ✩  │                       𝑅𝑖𝑒𝑚𝑎𝑛𝑛 𝐶𝑢𝑟𝑣𝑎𝑡𝑢𝑟𝑒 𝑇𝑒𝑛𝑠𝑜𝑟                       │  ✩
      ✩  └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘  ✩
      ✩                   ╔════════════════════════════════════╗                   ✩
      ✩                   ║ In order to typeset, invoke [:fmt] ║                   ✩
      ✩                   ╚════════════════════════════════════╝                   ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  Note that you can make use of the Language Server features in Helix:      ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩    ● Syntax errors will show inline diagnostics                            ✩
      ✩    ● [space+k] will give you a box with an info about the command under    ✩
      ✩      the caret (or the docuheader if it’s a user macro/lambda)             ✩
      ✩    ● [gd] will jump to definition                                          ✩
      ✩    ● “Intellisense” works                                                  ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  Helix  uses the compiled 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες  tree-sitter grammar for syntax  highli-  ✩
      ✩  ghting,  and the LSP  server for the  rest, which  is  in contrast  with  ✩
      ✩  VScode, which uses the LSP server for everything, including highlighting  ✩
      ✩  via semantic tokens). The  tree-sitter-based highlighting is faster (and  ✩
      ✩  doesn’t need Node), but the LSP highlighting is more complete.            ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩                  ___          _     ___     _                              ✩
      ✩                 | __|___ _ _ | |_  / __|___| |_ _  _ _ __                  ✩
      ✩                 | _|/ _ | ' \|  _| \__ / -_)  _| || | '_ \                 ✩
      ✩                 |_| \___|_||_|\__| |___\___|\__|\_,_| .__/                 ✩
      ✩                       For perfect visual experience |_|                    ✩
      ✩  /....................................................................../  ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  Not all  monospaced fonts were created equal – some are better for gene-  ✩
      ✩  ral coding, some for math and box  drawing, some are just  horrible, and  ✩
      ✩  some are flawless. The crucial font qualities for 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες are:             ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩    ● Unicode coverage                                                      ✩
      ✩      ○ Math symbols, greek, math alphabets – italic, bold, italic,         ✩
      ✩        blackboard                                                          ✩
      ✩      ○ Box drawing properly descending from VT100 (continuous scanlines)   ✩
      ✩        ○ Some multi-line operators use the 9th scanline glyph in the       ✩
      ✩          unicode mode, but this can be overriden with \cmd.                ✩
      ✩      ○ You can increase the coverage of any font by specifing fallback     ✩
      ✩        fonts (more on that we talk about settping up VSCode)               ✩
      ✩    ● True monospace advance metrics                                        ✩
      ✩      ○ Usually the “Term” version of the typeface                          ✩
      ✩      ○ Terminal emulators don’t use advance metrics (they align            ✩
      ✩        characters to a grid), but it is very important for graphical       ✩
      ✩        editors such as VSCode, which are capable of rendering              ✩
      ✩        proportional fonts. If you only work in the terminal, this doesn’t  ✩
      ✩        need to concern you.                                                ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  Here are the  fonts that are fully  compatible with 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες  and work wi-  ✩
      ✩  thout  any  fallbacks (meaning they  themselves make good  fallbacks for  ✩
      ✩  your preferred font):                                                     ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩    ┌──────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────┐    ✩
      ✩    │     Font     │ Comment                                           │    ✩
      ✩    ╞══════════════╪═══════════════════════════════════════════════════╡    ✩
      ✩    │ PragmataPro  │ This is a paid font, but by far the most  comple- │    ✩
      ✩    │ Mono         │ te, legible, and correct  monospaced font availa- │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ ble.  Despite being a condensed  font, it is more │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ legible  than most wide fonts, and is also visua- │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ lly very pretty.                                  │    ✩
      ✩    │              │                                                   │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ Fortunately  there  are free  alternatives listed │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ below.                                            │    ✩
      ✩    ├──────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────┤    ✩
      ✩    │  JuliaMono   │ A very  pretty, warm  font that was  designed for │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ the  Julia  programming  language. The  Julia la- │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ nguage uses unicode math symbols as syntax, hence │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ the font’s unicode  coverage is at the same level │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ as that of PragramataPro.                         │    ✩
      ✩    │              │                                                   │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ The typeface is less  analytical than Pragmata or │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ Iosefka,  and will make a good  fallback for font │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ with a similar feel.                              │    ✩
      ✩    │              │                                                   │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ One  unsatisfying  thing about  JuliaMono is that │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ its scanline  characters are not fully  continous │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ (don’t form a clear  uninterrupted line when next │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ to each  other). In fact the  glyphs that is uses │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ look  like  stubs and  are visually  inconsistent │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ with  other  similar  characters. Because of this │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ there’s  a  \cmd{julia}  macro that replaces  the │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ scanline with an underscore (also not continuous, │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ but more similar to the rest of the font).        │    ✩
      ✩    ├──────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────┤    ✩
      ✩    │ Iosevka Term │ Iosevka Term Extended is basically an open-source │    ✩
      ✩    │ Extended     │ alternative  to  PragmataPro. It has an extensive │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ Unicode coverage, and its metrics are  meticulou- │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ sly  monospaced. It also has both a condensed and │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ regular (“Extended”) family.                      │    ✩
      ✩    │              │                                                   │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ A tiny ommission in Iosefka – it doesn’t have the │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ math calligraphy alphabet, so I recommend you use │    ✩
      ✩    │              │ Julia Mono as a fallback in case you need it.     │    ✩
      ✩    ├──────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────┤    ✩
      ✩    │ Iosevka Term │ Same as above, but condensed.                     │    ✩
      ✩    ├──────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────┤    ✩
      ✩    │ Iosevka Term │ Same  as  Iosefka Term  Extended, but the  glyphs │    ✩
      ✩    │ Extended     │ have serifs (think of Courier).                   │    ✩
      ✩    │ Slab         │                                                   │    ✩
      ✩    ├──────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────┤    ✩
      ✩    │ Iosevka Term │ You guessed it!                                   │    ✩
      ✩    │ Slab         │                                                   │    ✩
      ✩    └──────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────────┘    ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩                        ___            _ _    _                             ✩
      ✩                       / __|__ _ _____(_) |__| |__ _                        ✩
      ✩                      | (__/ _` (_-<_-< | / _` / _` |                       ✩
      ✩                       \___\__,_/__/__|_|_\__,_\__,_|                       ✩
      ✩                Strange is the night where black stars rise…                ✩
      ✩  /....................................................................../  ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  Cassilda is a 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες  orchestrator – it allows  you to specify  where to  ✩
      ✩  render  the output of what piece of source  code. It extends  the 𝐻𝑦𝑎δες  ✩
      ✩  syntax with two types of directives:                                      ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩                      𝑙𝑎𝑏𝑒𝑙 – labels segments of code                       ✩
      ✩  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐  ✩
      ✩  │ 1:  │  label fresnel_sine                                            │  ✩
      ✩  │ 2:  │                                                                │  ✩
      ✩  │ 3:  │      Fresnel Sine Integral:                                    │  ✩
      ✩  │ 4:  │                                                                │  ✩
      ✩  │ 5:  │      $ \fn{S}(x) = \int_0^x                                    │  ✩
      ✩  │ 6:  │        \sin\left(\frac{\pi t^2}{2}\right) dt $                 │  ✩
      ✩  │ 7:  │                                                                │  ✩
      ✩  │ 8:  │      Taylor expansion:                                         │  ✩
      ✩  │ 9:  │                                                                │  ✩
      ✩  │ 10: │      $ \fn{S}(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty                           │  ✩
      ✩  │ 11: │        \frac{(-1)^n \left(\pi / 2\right)^{2n+1} x^{4n+3}}      │  ✩
      ✩  │ 12: │        {(4n+3)(2n+1)!} $                                       │  ✩
      ✩  │ 13: │                                                                │  ✩
      ✩  │ 14: │  end                                                           │  ✩
      ✩  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘  ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩                𝑟𝑒𝑓𝑒𝑟𝑒𝑛𝑐𝑒 – marks where a label will render                 ✩
      ✩  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐  ✩
      ✩  │ 1:  │  /* cassilda: fresnel_sine                                     │  ✩
      ✩  │ 2:  │   */                                                           │  ✩
      ✩  │ 3:  │  double fresnel_sine(double x) {                               │  ✩
      ✩  │ 4:  │      double sum = 0.0;                                         │  ✩
      ✩  │ 5:  │      double term = (M_PI / 2.0) * x * x * x / 3.0;             │  ✩
      ✩  │ 6:  │      sum = term;                                               │  ✩
      ✩  │ 7:  │                                                                │  ✩
      ✩  │ 8:  │      for (int n = 1; n < 25 && fabs(term) > 1e-15; ++n) {      │  ✩
      ✩  │ 9:  │          term *= -(M_PI * M_PI / 4.0) * (x * x * x * x);       │  ✩
      ✩  │ 10: │          term /= (2 * n) * (2 * n + 1);                        │  ✩
      ✩  │ 11: │          term *= (4 * n - 1) / (double)(4 * n + 3);            │  ✩
      ✩  │ 12: │          sum += term;                                          │  ✩
      ✩  │ 13: │      }                                                         │  ✩
      ✩  │ 14: │      return sum;                                               │  ✩
      ✩  │ 15: │  }                                                             │  ✩
      ✩  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘  ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  In 𝐻𝑒𝑙𝑖𝑥, for file  extensions other than [.cld], the  standard Cassilda  ✩
      ✩  formatter command ([:fmt]) cannot be used to render, because, for insta-  ✩
      ✩  nce, [.c] files will use the C language  formatter, etc.; install.sh re-  ✩
      ✩  gisters a separate  command  for this  purpose in config.toml:  [<Space-  ✩
      ✩  >-<TAB>]. If our target file is a [.cld] file,  invoking [:fmt] will re-  ✩
      ✩  nder all references in it. VSCode doesn’t make a difference in this, and  ✩
      ✩  will gladly run Cassilda on any file with any  configured extension upon  ✩
      ✩  saving. The Cassilda binary invocation used by both 𝐻𝑒𝑙𝑖𝑥 and the VSCode  ✩
      ✩  extension is:                                                             ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐  ✩
      ✩  │ > cassilda --find-config process -                                   │  ✩
      ✩  └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘  ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  The “-“ instructs Cassilda to run in a pipe mode instead of operating on  ✩
      ✩  a file, and “process” instructs cassilda to render all references in the  ✩
      ✩  input in place  and return the  resulting content. (See  “cassilda help”  ✩
      ✩  for usage.)                                                               ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  The  important part  here is “--find-config”. It switches  Cassilda to a  ✩
      ✩  “repo”  mode,  where she  doesn’t fail  when the  “fresnel_sine” segment  ✩
      ✩  isn’t  defined in the  processed file (or stdin), but goes on a quest to  ✩
      ✩  find it elsewhere. It tries the following:                                ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩    ● the current file                                                      ✩
      ✩    ● .cld files in the current directory                                   ✩
      ✩    ● walk up the directory structure until                                 ✩
      ✩      ○ home directory or root or repo root is reached                      ✩
      ✩      ○ or [.cassilda.json] is found                                        ✩
      ✩        ○ look in the library specified in there                            ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  In  our case, the  “fresnel_sine” label is stored in one of the  library  ✩
      ✩  directories that is defined in the found config, so:                      ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐  ✩
      ✩  │ 1:  │  /* cassilda: fresnel_sine                                     │  ✩
      ✩  │ 2:  │   * Fresnel Sine Integral:                                     │  ✩
      ✩  │ 3:  │   *                                                            │  ✩
      ✩  │ 4:  │   *         𝑥      ⎛    2  ⎞                                   │  ✩
      ✩  │ 5:  │   *         ⌠      ⎜  π𝑡   ⎟                                   │  ✩
      ✩  │ 6:  │   * S(𝑥) =  ⎮  sin ⎜ ───── ⎟ 𝑑𝑡                                │  ✩
      ✩  │ 7:  │   *         ⌡      ⎜   2   ⎟                                   │  ✩
      ✩  │ 8:  │   *         0      ⎝       ⎠                                   │  ✩
      ✩  │ 9:  │   *                                                            │  ✩
      ✩  │ 10: │   * Taylor expansion:                                          │  ✩
      ✩  │ 11: │   *                                                            │  ✩
      ✩  │ 12: │   *          ∞         𝑛       2𝑛 + 1 4𝑛 + 3                   │  ✩
      ✩  │ 13: │   *         ───    (-1) (π / 2)      𝑥                         │  ✩
      ✩  │ 14: │   * S(𝑥) =  ╲     ───────────────────────────                  │  ✩
      ✩  │ 15: │   *         ╱⎽⎽        (4𝑛 + 3)(2𝑛 + 1)!                       │  ✩
      ✩  │ 16: │   *        𝑛 = 0                                               │  ✩
      ✩  │ 17: │   *                                                            │  ✩
      ✩  │ 18: │   */                                                           │  ✩
      ✩  │ 19: │  double fresnel_sine(double x) {                               │  ✩
      ✩  │ 20: │      double sum = 0.0;                                         │  ✩
      ✩  │ 21: │      double term = (M_PI / 2.0) * x * x * x / 3.0;             │  ✩
      ✩  │ 22: │      sum = term;                                               │  ✩
      ✩  │ 23: │                                                                │  ✩
      ✩  │ 24: │      for (int n = 1; n < 25 && fabs(term) > 1e-15; ++n) {      │  ✩
      ✩  │ 25: │          term *= -(M_PI * M_PI / 4.0) * (x * x * x * x);       │  ✩
      ✩  │ 26: │          term /= (2 * n) * (2 * n + 1);                        │  ✩
      ✩  │ 27: │          term *= (4 * n - 1) / (double)(4 * n + 3);            │  ✩
      ✩  │ 28: │          sum += term;                                          │  ✩
      ✩  │ 29: │      }                                                         │  ✩
      ✩  │ 30: │      return sum;                                               │  ✩
      ✩  │ 31: │  }                                                             │  ✩
      ✩  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘  ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  Cassilda prefixes the rendered lines with a single NBSP character, which  ✩
      ✩  allows it to be idempotent to repeated processing, i.e. it will only add  ✩
      ✩  or update  the output under the  reference – it will never  duplicate or  ✩
      ✩  corrupt it.                                                               ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  One of the  intended usages of Cassilda  is  to render a .cld  file into  ✩
      ✩  itself,  making it a sort of a self-executable  notebook (like Jupyter).  ✩
      ✩  This very file is an example (although not a very good one since it sho-  ✩
      ✩  ves  the entire  contnet into a single segment  rendered at the  top for  ✩
      ✩  your convenience – see the math primer for a better example).             ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  The [.cassilda.json] config file may look like this:                      ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐  ✩
      ✩  │ 1:  │  {                                                             │  ✩
      ✩  │ 2:  │    "include_subdirs": true,                                    │  ✩
      ✩  │ 3:  │    "cache_path": ".cassilda-cache",                            │  ✩
      ✩  │ 4:  │    "library_dirs": [                                           │  ✩
      ✩  │ 5:  │      "library_directory",                                      │  ✩
      ✩  │ 6:  │      "another_one"                                             │  ✩
      ✩  │ 7:  │    ],                                                          │  ✩
      ✩  │ 8:  │    "library_files": [                                          │  ✩
      ✩  │ 9:  │      "lib1.cld", "other.cld"                                   │  ✩
      ✩  │ 10: │    ]                                                           │  ✩
      ✩  │ 11: │    "target_prefix": {                                          │  ✩
      ✩  │ 12: │      ".c": " * ",                                              │  ✩
      ✩  │ 13: │      ".h": " * ",                                              │  ✩
      ✩  │ 14: │      ".py": "# ",                                              │  ✩
      ✩  │ 15: │      ".go": "// "                                              │  ✩
      ✩  │ 16: │    }                                                           │  ✩
      ✩  │ 17: │  }                                                             │  ✩
      ✩  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘  ✩
      ✩  ┌─────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────┐  ✩
      ✩  │  𝑖𝑛𝑐𝑙𝑢𝑑𝑒_𝑠𝑢𝑏𝑑𝑖𝑟𝑒𝑐𝑡𝑜𝑟𝑖𝑒𝑠 │ Also searches the  sub-directiories of the │  ✩
      ✩  │                         │ directories defined in 𝑙𝑖𝑏𝑟𝑎𝑟𝑦_𝑓𝑖𝑙𝑒𝑠.      │  ✩
      ✩  ├─────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────┤  ✩
      ✩  │              𝑐𝑎𝑐ℎ𝑒_𝑝𝑎𝑡ℎ │ The path to the file where Cassilda should │  ✩
      ✩  │                         │ store  discovered segments and  their che- │  ✩
      ✩  │                         │ cksums for better lookup efficiency.       │  ✩
      ✩  ├─────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────┤  ✩
      ✩  │            𝑙𝑖𝑏𝑟𝑎𝑟𝑦_𝑑𝑖𝑟𝑠 │ A list of list directories with .cld files │  ✩
      ✩  │                         │ which Cassila  searches for labels (segme- │  ✩
      ✩  │                         │ nts) when rendering.                       │  ✩
      ✩  ├─────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────┤  ✩
      ✩  │           𝑙𝑖𝑏𝑟𝑎𝑟𝑦_𝑓𝑖𝑙𝑒𝑠 │ An explicit  list of .cld files to be sea- │  ✩
      ✩  │                         │ rched    through    before    looking   in │  ✩
      ✩  │                         │ 𝑙𝑖𝑏𝑟𝑎𝑟𝑦_𝑑𝑖𝑟𝑠.                              │  ✩
      ✩  ├─────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────┤  ✩
      ✩  │           𝑡𝑎𝑟𝑔𝑒𝑡_𝑝𝑟𝑒𝑓𝑖𝑥 │ A map of file  extensions to prefixes that │  ✩
      ✩  │                         │ are  prepended to every line of the rende- │  ✩
      ✩  │                         │ ring output. This is primary meant to spe- │  ✩
      ✩  │                         │ cify  comment  prefixes.  If these  aren’t │  ✩
      ✩  │                         │ specifies,  Cassilda uses the  default for │  ✩
      ✩  │                         │ the extension if she knows it.             │  ✩
      ✩  └─────────────────────────┴────────────────────────────────────────────┘  ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩                 ___ _  _ ___     ___    _ _ _                              ✩
      ✩                / __| || |_ _|   | __|__| (_) |_ ___ _ _ ___                ✩
      ✩               | (_ | || || |    | _|/ _` | |  _/ _ | '_(_-<                ✩
      ✩                \___|\__/|___|   |___\__,_|_|\__\___|_| /__/                ✩
      ✩                          Help, can’t exit vim :‘(                          ✩
      ✩  /....................................................................../  ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩                             VSCode Integration                             ✩
      ✩                             ──────────────────                             ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  You will want to install the Hyades  extension, and you will need to run  ✩
      ✩  the install script as well, since it installs  the two binaries  and the  ✩
      ✩  LSP server to the location where the extension expects to find them.      ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  Alternatively  you can  link the built  extension from the  repo to your  ✩
      ✩  local VSCode installation:                                                ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐  ✩
      ✩  │ 1:  │  ~> cd hyades                                                  │  ✩
      ✩  │ 2:  │  hyades> cd hyades-vscode-ext                                  │  ✩
      ✩  │ 3:  │  hyades> ./install.local.sh                                    │  ✩
      ✩  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘  ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  The extension requires some basic settings in [.vscode/settings.json]:    ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  ┌─────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐  ✩
      ✩  │ 1:  │  {                                                             │  ✩
      ✩  │ 2:  │    "files.associations": {                                     │  ✩
      ✩  │ 3:  │      "*.cld": "cassilda",                                      │  ✩
      ✩  │ 4:  │      "*.hy": "cassilda"                                        │  ✩
      ✩  │ 5:  │    },                                                          │  ✩
      ✩  │ 6:  │    "[cassilda]": {                                             │  ✩
      ✩  │ 7:  │      "editor.bracketPairColorization.enabled": false           │  ✩
      ✩  │ 8:  │      // + Font metrics (see below)                             │  ✩
      ✩  │ 9:  │    },                                                          │  ✩
      ✩  │ 10: │    "cassilda.processOnSave": true,                             │  ✩
      ✩  │ 11: │    "cassilda.processExtensions": [                             │  ✩
      ✩  │ 12: │      ".cld",                                                   │  ✩
      ✩  │ 13: │      ".c",                                                     │  ✩
      ✩  │ 14: │      ".cpp",                                                   │  ✩
      ✩  │ 15: │      ".h",                                                     │  ✩
      ✩  │ 16: │      ".hpp",                                                   │  ✩
      ✩  │ 17: │      ".py",                                                    │  ✩
      ✩  │ 18: │      ".js",                                                    │  ✩
      ✩  │ 19: │      ".ts"                                                     │  ✩
      ✩  │ 20: │    ],                                                          │  ✩
      ✩  │ 21: │    // Optional exclusion:                                      │  ✩
      ✩  │ 22: │    "cassilda.processOnSaveExclude": [                          │  ✩
      ✩  │ 23: │      "**/wasm/**"                                              │  ✩
      ✩  │ 24: │    ],                                                          │  ✩
      ✩  │ 25: │    // Optional override:                                       │  ✩
      ✩  │ 26: │    //"cassilda.executablePath": ""                             │  ✩
      ✩  │ 27: │  }                                                             │  ✩
      ✩  └─────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘  ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩  As  metioned  in  𝐹𝑜𝑛𝑡  𝑆𝑒𝑡𝑢𝑝, a proportional-capable  text editor  like  ✩
      ✩  VSCode will not align characters to a grid, and will obey the font adva-  ✩
      ✩  nce  metrics. You will  also have to experiment  with the baseline  skip  ✩
      ✩  (“lineHeight”) in order to have  connectable characters sit perfectly on  ✩
      ✩  top of each other. For the font I recommended  I’ve found the  following  ✩
      ✩  settings to produce acceptable rendering:                                 ✩
      ✩                                                                            ✩
      ✩    ┌──────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────┐    ✩
      ✩    │     𝐹𝑜𝑛𝑡     │                     𝑆𝑒𝑡𝑡𝑖𝑛𝑔𝑠                      │    ✩
      ✩    ╞══════════════╪═══════╤═══════════════════════════════════════════╡    ✩
      ✩    │ PragmataPro  │   1:  │  "[cassilda]": {                          │    ✩
      ✩    │ Mono         │   2:  │    "editor.fontFamily": "PragmataPro Mono │    ✩
      ✩    │              │   3:  │    "editor.fontWeight": "10",             │    ✩
      ✩    │              │   4:  │                                           │    ✩
      ✩    │              │   5:  │    // Use lineHeight 15 for perfect math  │    ✩
      ✩    │              │   6:  │    // vert. alignment, but worse visual   │    ✩
      ✩    │              │   7:  │    // effect from prose paragraphs.       │    ✩
      ✩    │              │   8:  │    "editor.lineHeight": 16,               │    ✩
      ✩    │              │   9:  │    "editor.fontSize": 14                  │    ✩
      ✩    │              │   10: │  },                                       │    ✩
      ✩    ├──────────────┼───────┼───────────────────────────────────────────┤    ✩
      ✩    │  JuliaMono   │   1:  │  "[cassilda]": {                          │    ✩
      ✩    │              │   2:  │    "editor.fontFamily": "JuliaMono",      │    ✩
      ✩    │              │   3:  │    "editor.fontWeight": "300",            │    ✩
      ✩    │              │   4:  │    "editor.lineHeight": 18,               │    ✩
      ✩    │              │   5:  │    "editor.fontSize": 13                  │    ✩
      ✩    │              │   6:  │  },                                       │    ✩
      ✩    ├──────────────┼───────┼───────────────────────────────────────────┤    ✩
      ✩    │ Iosevka Term │   1:  │  "[cassilda]": {                          │    ✩
      ✩    │ Extended     │   2:  │    "editor.fontFamily":                   │    ✩
      ✩    │              │   3:  │      "Iosevka Term Extended, JuliaMono",  │    ✩
      ✩    │              │   4:  │    "editor.fontWeight": "200",            │    ✩
      ✩    │              │   5:  │    "editor.lineHeight": 16,               │    ✩
      ✩    │              │   6:  │    "editor.fontSize": 13                  │    ✩
      ✩    │              │   7:  │  },                                       │    ✩
      ✩    ├──────────────┼───────┴───────────────────────────────────────────┤    ✩
      ✩    │ Iosevka Term │ Same as above                                     │    ✩
      ✩    ├──────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────┤    ✩
      ✩    │ Iosevka Term │ Same as Iosefka Term Extended                     │    ✩
      ✩    │ Extended     │                                                   │    ✩
      ✩    │ Slab         │                                                   │    ✩
      ✩    └──────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────────┘    ✩
