    \begin{output} % Remember that any macro can use the LaTeX environment invocation syntax

    \vskip{0}
    \begin{vbox}
        \child[center]{\figlet{Hyades}}
        \xvskip{-1}
        \child[center]{\hskip{12}A Quick Overview}
        \child{\hrule{/}{.}{/}}
    \end{vbox}

    First of all, whether you've made it to this notebook because you need to
    include pretty math in your code comments/documentation, or you want to
    send it via e-mail and don't want to install a 5GB TeX distribution, or
    send PDFs/screenshots, thank you for showing interest in \hyades.

    \macro<\sec{x}>{
        \vskip{2}
        \culn{${x}}
        \vskip{1}
    }

    \sec{What Is This?}

    A lightweight CLI program that allows you to render TeX into multi-line text, and much more!

    $$ f^{(n)}(a) = \frac{n!}{2\pi i} \oint_\gamma \frac{f(z)}{(z-a)^{n+1}} \, dz $$

    This $\uparrow$ is what you'll get on the standard output if you pipe this piece of
    LaTeX math into hyades:

\indent[2]{\verb|$$ f^{(n)}(a) = \frac{n!}{2\pi i}
   \oint_\gamma \frac{f(z)}{(z-a)^{n+1}} \, dz $$|}

    Moreover, you can have it automatically rendered to your source code as a comment using
    Cassilda (yes, you've correctly recognized the cosmic horror references). We have a VSCode
    extension, and an installer for Helix and Neovim!

    \vskip{1}
    \center{\boxed{\center{%
        --- \textit{What if I don't know TeX?} ---

        \begin{vbox}
            \child[45]{
                \hyades{} has both an online MCP server, and an offline
                MCP binary. You can add either to your AI, which will
                equip it with the \hyades{} \textit{render} tool.

                \center{\Boxed{https://hyades-mcp.apg.workers.dev/mcp}}
                
                You can then tell it to write the math for you, e.g.:
                \textit{Use Hyades to write a proof of the Gaussian Integral}

                \center{--- or ---}

                \textit{Could you use Hyades to describe the math this code
                performs, and attach it as documentation headers?}
            }
        \end{vbox}
        }
    }}

    The rest of this primer will take you through the basic setup and usage, and
    if you've not had enough by the end of it, there are follow-up guides with in-depth
    focus on specific areas.

    \vskip{1}
    \begin{vbox}
        \child[center]{\figlet{Setup}}
        \xvskip{-1}
        \child[left]{\hskip{22}How to Get Started}
        \child{\hrule{/}{.}{/}}
    \end{vbox}

    Download the release for your architecture directly from GitHub:

    \center{
        \Tightframe{https://github.com/apology-is-policy/hyades/releases}
    }

    The release ships with install scripts for MacOS, Linux, and Windows:

    \center{\tightframe{%
        \# Unixes:\\
        editor-configs/install.sh\\
        \# Windows:\\
        .\textbackslash{}editor-configs\textbackslash{}install.ps1}
    }

    This will:

    \indent[2]{\fancylist{
        - Install the two core executables and add them to your PATH.
        - If there's a Helix installation, it will register itself with Helix
        - The same with Neovim
        - It will typeset something to the console to test the installation.
    }}

    You are invited to build from source, which is very easy -- after all, \hyades{} has
    no binary dependencies whatsover.

    
    \vskip{1}
    \begin{vbox}
        \child[center]{\figlet{Running}}
        \xvskip{-1}
        \child[left]{\hskip{21}I'm okay to go, okay to go!}
        \child{\hrule{/}{.}{/}}
    \end{vbox}

    Let's use \textit{Helix} for our "Hello World", since it works out of the box and VSCode
    requires an extension and some tinkering with the settings. \textit{Helix} is a modal editor that
    you can download here:

    \center{\tightframe{https://helix-editor.com}}

    Re-run the install script -- now that you actualy have \textit{Helix}, \hyades{} will install itself
    into it. Now create a new Cassilda file:

    \frame{{} \> hx hello.cld}

    Once in \textit{Helix}, switch to some normal theme that supports syntax highlighting:
    \[:theme dark_plus\], and we're ready for our program:

    \listing{
    \@{}hello\vskip{1}
\verb|
The \textbf{Riemann curvature tensor} is a central
mathematical tool in the theory of general relativity.

\subtitle[\textit{Riemann Curvature Tensor}]{$$
    R^\rho{}_{\sigma\mu\nu} =
    \partial_\mu\Gamma^\rho_{\nu\sigma} -
    \partial_\nu\Gamma^\rho_{\mu\sigma} +
    \Gamma^\rho_{\mu\lambda}\Gamma^\lambda_{\nu\sigma} -
    \Gamma^\rho_{\nu\lambda}\Gamma^\lambda_{\mu\sigma}
$$}
|\vskip{1}
\@{}end\\
\@{}cassilda: hello
}\vskip{1}

    \begin{hbox}
        \child[center]{↓↓↓}
        \child[center]{↓↓↓}
        \child[center]{↓↓↓}
        \child[center]{↓↓↓}
        \child[center]{↓↓↓}
    \end{hbox}
    \frame{
    The \textbf{Riemann curvature tensor} is a central mathematical tool in the theory of
    general relativity.
    
    \subtitle[\textit{Riemann Curvature Tensor}]{$$
        R^\rho{}_{\sigma\mu\nu} =
        \partial_\mu\Gamma^\rho_{\nu\sigma} -
        \partial_\nu\Gamma^\rho_{\mu\sigma} +
        \Gamma^\rho_{\mu\lambda}\Gamma^\lambda_{\nu\sigma} -
        \Gamma^\rho_{\nu\lambda}\Gamma^\lambda_{\mu\sigma}
    $$}}

    \center{\Tightframe{In order to typeset,
    invoke [:fmt]}}

    Note that you can make use of the Language Server features in Helix:

    \indent[2]{\fancylist{
        - Syntax errors will show inline diagnostics
        - [space+k] will give you a box with an info about the command under the caret
          (or the docuheader if it's a user macro/lambda)
        - [gd] will jump to definition
        - "Intellisense" works
    }}

    Helix uses the compiled \hyades{} tree-sitter grammar for syntax highlighting,
    and the LSP server for the rest, which is in contrast with VScode, which uses the LSP server
    for everything, including highlighting via semantic tokens). The tree-sitter-based
    highlighting is faster (and doesn't need Node), but the LSP highlighting is more complete.

% ----------------------------------------------FONTS---------------------------------------------

    \vskip{1}
    \begin{vbox}
        \child[center]{\figlet{Font Setup}}
        \xvskip{-1}
        \child[left]{\hskip{21}For perfect visual experience}
        \child{\hrule{/}{.}{/}}
    \end{vbox}

    Not all monospaced fonts were created equal -- some are better for general coding, some
    for math and box drawing, some are just horrible, and some are flawless. The crucial
    font qualities for \hyades{} are:

    \indent[2]{\fancylist{
        - Unicode coverage
          - Math symbols, greek, math alphabets -- italic, bold, italic, blackboard
          - Box drawing properly descending from VT100 (continuous scanlines)
            - Some multi-line operators use the 9th scanline glyph in the unicode mode,
              but this can be overriden with \cmd{setsym}.
          - You can increase the coverage of any font by specifing fallback fonts (more on
            that we talk about settping up VSCode)
        - True monospace advance metrics
          - Usually the "Term" version of the typeface
          - Terminal emulators don't use advance metrics (they align characters to
            a grid), but it is very important for graphical editors such as VSCode,
            which are capable of rendering proportional fonts. If you only work in the
            terminal, this doesn't need to concern you.
    }}

    Here are the fonts that are fully compatible with \hyades{} and work without any
    fallbacks (meaning they themselves make good fallbacks for your preferred font):


    \hcenter[\sub{\width, 4}]{
    \table[pad:{l:1,r:1}]{
        \row[frame:{b:double}]{
            \col[width:14][align:c]{Font}
            \col[align:l]{Comment}
        }
        \row[frame:{b:single}]{
            \col{PragmataPro Mono}
            \col{This is a paid font, but by far the most complete, legible, and correct monospaced
                 font available. Despite being a condensed font, it is more legible than most wide fonts,
                 and is also visually very pretty.
            
                 Fortunately there are free alternatives listed below.
            }    
        }
        \row[frame:{b:single}]{
            \col{JuliaMono}
            \col[align:l]{
                A very pretty, warm font that was designed for the Julia programming language. The
                Julia language uses unicode math symbols as syntax, hence the font's unicode coverage
                is at the same level as that of PragramataPro.

                The typeface is less analytical than Pragmata or Iosefka, and will make a good
                fallback for font with a similar feel.

                One unsatisfying thing about JuliaMono is that its scanline characters are not
                fully continous (don't form a clear uninterrupted line when next to each other).
                In fact the glyphs that is uses look like stubs and are visually inconsistent with
                other similar characters. Because of this there's a \cmd{hint_font}\{julia\} macro
                that replaces the scanline with an underscore (also not continuous, but more similar
                to the rest of the font).
            } 
        }
        \row[frame:{b:single}]{
            \col{Iosevka Term Extended}
            \col{Iosevka Term Extended is basically an open-source alternative to PragmataPro.
                 It has an extensive Unicode coverage, and its metrics are meticulously monospaced.
                 It also has both a condensed and regular ("Extended") family.

                 A tiny ommission in Iosefka -- it doesn't have the math calligraphy alphabet,
                 so I recommend you use Julia Mono as a fallback in case you need it.
            }
        }
        \row[frame:{b:single}]{
            \col{Iosevka Term}
            \col{Same as above, but condensed.} 
        }

        \row[frame:{b:single}]{
            \col{Iosevka Term Extended Slab}
            \col{Same as Iosefka Term Extended, but the glyphs have serifs (think of Courier).} 
        }

        \row[frame:{b:single}]{
            \col{Iosevka Term Slab}
            \col{You guessed it!} 
        }
     }
    }


% --------------------------------------------CASSILDA-------------------------------------------

 
    \vskip{1}
    \begin{vbox}
        \child[center]{\figlet{Cassilda}}
        \xvskip{-1}
        \child[center]{Strange is the night where black stars rise...}
        \child{\hrule{/}{.}{/}}
    \end{vbox}

    Cassilda is a \hyades{} orchestrator -- it allows you to specify where to render the
    output of what piece of source code. It extends the \hyades{} syntax with two types
    of directives:

    \supertitle[\textit{label} -- labels segments of code]{%
    \fancylisting{%
\@{}label~fresnel_sine\vskip{1}
\verb|
    Fresnel Sine Integral:

    $ \fn{S}(x) = \int_0^x
      \sin\left(\frac{\pi t^2}{2}\right) dt $

    Taylor expansion:

    $ \fn{S}(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty
      \frac{(-1)^n \left(\pi / 2\right)^{2n+1} x^{4n+3}}
      {(4n+3)(2n+1)!} $|\vskip{1}
\@{}end}}
    \vskip{1}
    \supertitle[\textit{reference} -- marks where a label will render]{%
    \fancylisting{

/*~\@{}cassilda:~fresnel_sine
\verb| */
double fresnel_sine(double x) {
    double sum = 0.0;
    double term = (M_PI / 2.0) * x * x * x / 3.0;
    sum = term;

    for (int n = 1; n < 25 && fabs(term) > 1e-15; ++n) {
        term *= -(M_PI * M_PI / 4.0) * (x * x * x * x);
        term /= (2 * n) * (2 * n + 1);
        term *= (4 * n - 1) / (double)(4 * n + 3);
        sum += term;
    }
    return sum;
}|}}

In \textit{Helix}, for file extensions other than [.cld], the standard Cassilda
formatter command ([:fmt]) cannot be used to render, because, for instance, [.c] files
will use the C language formatter, etc.; install.sh registers a separate command
for this purpose in config.toml: [<Space>-<TAB>]. If our target file is a [.cld] file,
invoking [:fmt] will render all references in it. VSCode doesn't make a difference in
this, and will gladly run Cassilda on any file with any configured extension upon
saving. The Cassilda binary invocation used by both \textit{Helix} and the VSCode extension is:

\macro<\dd>{\verb|--|}

\frame{{} \> cassilda \dd find-config process -}

The "-" instructs Cassilda to run in a pipe mode instead of operating on a file,
and "process" instructs cassilda to render all references in the input in place
and return the resulting content. (See "cassilda help" for usage.)

The important part here is "\dd find-config". It switches Cassilda to a "repo"
mode, where she doesn't fail when the "fresnel_sine" segment isn't defined in
the processed file (or stdin), but goes on a quest to find it elsewhere. It
tries the following:

\indent[2]{\fancylist{
    - the current file
    - .cld files in the current directory
    - walk up the directory structure until
      - home directory or root or repo root is reached
      - or [.cassilda.json] is found
        - look in the library specified in there
}}

In our case, the "fresnel_sine" label is stored in one of the library directories
that is defined in the found config, so:

    \fancylisting{
/*~\@cassilda:~fresnel_sine
    \verb|
 * Fresnel Sine Integral:
 * 
 *         𝑥      ⎛    2  ⎞
 *         ⌠      ⎜  π𝑡   ⎟
 * S(𝑥) =  ⎮  sin ⎜ ───── ⎟ 𝑑𝑡
 *         ⌡      ⎜   2   ⎟
 *         0      ⎝       ⎠
 * 
 * Taylor expansion:
 * 
 *          ∞         𝑛       2𝑛 + 1 4𝑛 + 3
 *         ───    (-1) (π / 2)      𝑥
 * S(𝑥) =  ╲     ───────────────────────────
 *         ╱⎽⎽        (4𝑛 + 3)(2𝑛 + 1)!
 *        𝑛 = 0
 * 
 */
double fresnel_sine(double x) {
    double sum = 0.0;
    double term = (M_PI / 2.0) * x * x * x / 3.0;
    sum = term;

    for (int n = 1; n < 25 && fabs(term) > 1e-15; ++n) {
        term *= -(M_PI * M_PI / 4.0) * (x * x * x * x);
        term /= (2 * n) * (2 * n + 1);
        term *= (4 * n - 1) / (double)(4 * n + 3);
        sum += term;
    }
    return sum;
}|}

Cassilda prefixes the rendered lines with a single NBSP character, which allows it to be
idempotent to repeated processing, i.e. it will only add or update the output under the
reference -- it will never duplicate or corrupt it.

One of the intended usages of Cassilda is to render a .cld file into itself, making it
a sort of a self-executable notebook (like Jupyter). This very file is an example
(although not a very good one since it shoves the entire contnet into a single segment
rendered at the top for your convenience -- see the math primer for a better example).

The [.cassilda.json] config file may look like this:

\fancylisting{\verb|
{
  "include_subdirs": true,
  "cache_path": ".cassilda-cache",
  "library_dirs": [
    "library_directory",
    "another_one"
  ],
  "library_files": [
    "lib1.cld", "other.cld"
  ]
  "target_prefix": {
    ".c": " * ",
    ".h": " * ",
    ".py": "# ",
    ".go": "// "
  }
}
|}

\table[frame:single,pad:{l:1,r:1}]{
    \row[frame:single]{
        \col[width:25][align:r]{\textit{include_subdirectories}}
        \col{Also searches the sub-directiories of the directories defined in
             \textit{library_files}.}
    }
    \row{
        \col{\textit{cache_path}}
        \col{The path to the file where Cassilda should store discovered segments
             and their checksums for better lookup efficiency.}
    }
    \row{
        \col{\textit{library_dirs}}
        \col{A list of list directories with .cld files which Cassila searches
             for labels (segments) when rendering.}
    }
    \row{
        \col{\textit{library_files}}
        \col{An explicit list of .cld files to be searched through before looking
             in \textit{library_dirs}.}
    }
    \row{
        \col{\textit{target_prefix}}
        \col{A map of file extensions to prefixes that are prepended to every line
             of the rendering output. This is primary meant to specify comment prefixes.
             If these aren't specifies, Cassilda uses the default for the extension
             if she knows it.}
    }}


% ------------------------------------------EDITORS----------------------------------------------


    \vskip{1}
    \begin{vbox}
        \child[center]{\figlet{GUI~~Editors}}
        \xvskip{-1}
        \child[center]{Help, can't exit vim :'(}
        \child{\hrule{/}{.}{/}}
    \end{vbox}

    \sec{VSCode Integration}

    You will want to install the Hyades extension, and you will need to run the install
    script as well, since it installs the two binaries and the LSP server to the
    location where the extension expects to find them.

    Alternatively you can link the built extension from the repo to your local VSCode
    installation:
    
    \fancylisting{\verb|~> cd hyades
hyades> cd hyades-vscode-ext
hyades> ./install.local.sh
|}

    The extension requires some basic settings in [.vscode/settings.json]:

    \fancylisting{
    \verb|
{
  "files.associations": {
    "*.cld": "cassilda",
    "*.hy": "cassilda"
  },
  "[cassilda]": {
    "editor.bracketPairColorization.enabled": false
    // + Font metrics (see below)
  },
  "cassilda.processOnSave": true,
  "cassilda.processExtensions": [
    ".cld",
    ".c",
    ".cpp",
    ".h",
    ".hpp",
    ".py",
    ".js",
    ".ts"
  ],
  // Optional exclusion:
  "cassilda.processOnSaveExclude": [
    "**/wasm/**"
  ],
  // Optional override:
  //"cassilda.executablePath": ""
}|
}

As metioned in \textit{Font Setup}, a proportional-capable text editor like VSCode
will not align characters to a grid, and will obey the font advance metrics. You will
also have to experiment with the baseline skip ("lineHeight") in order to have
connectable characters sit perfectly on top of each other. For the font I recommended
I've found the following settings to produce acceptable rendering:

    \hcenter[\sub{\width, 4}]{
    \table[pad:{l:1,r:1}]{
        \row[frame:{b:double}]{
            \col[width:14][align:c]{\textit{Font}}
            \col[align:c]{\textit{Settings}}
        }
        \row[frame:{b:single}]{
            \col{PragmataPro Mono}
            \col[align:l]{

            \listing{\verb|
"[cassilda]": {
  "editor.fontFamily": "PragmataPro Mono",
  "editor.fontWeight": "10",

  // Use lineHeight 15 for perfect math
  // vert. alignment, but worse visual
  // effect from prose paragraphs.
  "editor.lineHeight": 16,
  "editor.fontSize": 14
},
|}
            }    
        }
        \row[frame:{b:single}]{
            \col{JuliaMono}
            \col[align:l]{
                \listing{\verb|
"[cassilda]": {
  "editor.fontFamily": "JuliaMono",
  "editor.fontWeight": "300",
  "editor.lineHeight": 18,
  "editor.fontSize": 13
},
|}
            } 
        }
        \row[frame:{b:single}]{
            \col{Iosevka Term Extended}
            \col{

                \listing{\verb|
"[cassilda]": {
  "editor.fontFamily":
    "Iosevka Term Extended, JuliaMono",
  "editor.fontWeight": "200",
  "editor.lineHeight": 16,
  "editor.fontSize": 13
},
|}
            }
        }
        \row[frame:{b:single}]{
            \col{Iosevka Term}
            \col{Same as above} 
        }

        \row[frame:{b:single}]{
            \col{Iosevka Term Extended Slab}
            \col{Same as Iosefka Term Extended} 
        }
     }
    }

    


